Algorithm 1 Modied-SAW function
Data: The matrix mat [m][n] and the weighting vector w[], α = m Result: Income vector for each network for (j = 0; j < m; j + +) do
for (i = 0; i < n; i + +) do
tab[i] = mat[i][j];
end
tabind = Sort(tab);
for (k = 0; k < T abind.length; k + +) do
income[tabind[k]] = income[tabind[k]] + (α − k) × w[k]
end
return income[];
end

Chapter 4: Network selection

73

Algorithm 2 The sort function of the M-SAW algorithm Data: vector tab[] Result: Sort function
int t[][]
double min;
int ind, cpt = 0, deb = 0;
inta = 0, nb = 0, val = 0;
while (deb < t.length) do while (tab[a] < 0) do
a + +;
end
min = tab[a]; ind = a;
for (inti = 0; i < tab.length; i + +) do if (min > tab[i] and tab[i] >= 0) then
min = tab[i]; ind = i; nb = 0;
end else if (min == tab[i] and a! = i) then
nb + +;
end end for (intp = deb; p < deb + nb + 1; p + +) do
tab[hah] = −1; hah + +;
for (inth = 0; h < 2; h + +) do if (h == 0) then
t[p][h] = val;
end else
t[p][h] = ind + cpt; cpt + +;
end end end
val + +; cpt = 0;
deb = deb + nb + 1;
end
return t;

In this work, we use two examples of each type of network to bring out the rank reversal problem and solve it with the proposed method. The values of the matrix used in for processing Table 3.3 is generated randomly based on the Table 3.2.

